results.description:
White Rock lake, upper spillway
Photo 1:  Forster's Tern On The Spillway
Finally photographed my first terns.  I'd watched them diving into the lake after fish before but all my attempts to capture that behavior were never in focus.  They were just too fast.  This time I spied several sitting on the spillway, an easier target.  The large ring-billed gulls show how small forster's terns are in comparison.
Photo 2:  Showing Off The Wings
One of the terns let me get a nice look at the wings as it stretched.   There were about 10 of them spread out among the ring-bills.
Photo 3:  My Feathers Crisscross When I Sit
When they sit down, the ends of their wing feathers crisscross behind them.  These birds will dive down from the air to snatch fish up and fly off.  So far, always too quickly for me to capture that.  Glad to have found them in resting mode.  
Photo 4:  My Black Ear-Patch Is Comma Shaped
There are several tern species that look alike in their summer breeding plumage.  But in the winter plumage, you can identify Forster's by the black ear patch in a comma shape.  You can see it clearly on the one walking in this shot.
